ol-begin}}\n{{col-break}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{Sister project links|North Florida|voy=North Florida}}\n{{Portal|Florida}}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Lamme |first1= Ary J. |last2= Oldakowski |first2= Raymond K. |title= Spinning a new geography of vernacular regional identity: Florida in the twenty-first century |journal= Southeastern Geographer |volume= 47 |issue= 2 |pages= 320\u2013340 |doi= 10.1353/sgo.2007.0029 |date= November 2007 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal |last1= Warf |first1= Barney |last2= Waddell |first2= Cynthia | title = Florida in the 2000 presidential election: historical precedents and contemporary landscapes | journal = [[Political Geography (journal)|Political Geography]] | volume = 21 | issue = 1 | pages = 85\u201390 | doi = 10.1016/S0962-6298(01)00063-4 | date = January 2002 | ref = harv }}\n* {{cite journal |author= Anthony J. Catanese Center for Urban and Environmental Solutions at Florida Atlantic University |year= 2006 |title= Charting the Course: Where is South Florida Heading? |publisher= [[Florida Atlantic University]] |url= http://www.soflo.fau.edu/course/report.pdf |accessdate= March 30, 2012 |url-status= dead |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20111216100938/http://www.soflo.fau.edu/course/report.pdf |archivedate= December 16, 2011 }}\n\n{{North Florida}}\n{{Florida}}\n\n [[Category:North Florida|01]]\n[[Category:Regions of Florida]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Region in Florida}}\n{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n|name = North Florida\n|settlement_type=[[Regions of Florida|Region]] of [[Florida]]\n|image_skyline =NorFLAcollage.png\n|imagesize=250px\n|image_caption= Top left to right: [[Florida State Capitol]] in [[Tallahassee]], [[Downtown Jacksonville|Downtown]] [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]], <br/> [[Flagler College]], [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]]  skyline<br/> Bottom left to right: [[Silver Springs Nature Theme Park]], and [[Big Lagoon State Park]]\n|image_map=North Florida map.png\n|image_map1=\n|map_caption=\n|map_caption1=\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = {{US}}\n|subdivision_type1      = State\n|subdivision_name1      = {{flag|Florida}}\n|subdivision_type2      = Largest city\n|subdivision_name2      = {{flagicon image|Flag of Jacksonville, Florida.svg}} [[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]\n|population_as_of       = 2010\n|population_total            = 3,753,144 (approximate area)<ref>{{cite web|title=Population by county|url=https://www.census.gov/cbdmap/|work=Interactive Map|publisher=U.S. Census|accessdate=17 July 2013}}</ref>\n}}\n\n'''North Florida''' is a [[Regions of the United States#Florida|region]] of the [[Southern United States|Southern]] [[U.S. state]] of [[Florida]], comprising the northernmost part of the state. It is one of Florida's three most common \"directional\" regions, along with [[South Florida]] and [[Central Florida]]. It includes [[Jacksonville]] and nearby localities in [[Northeast Florida]], an interior region known as [[North Central Florida]], and the [[Florida Panhandle]].\n\n==Geography==\n===Area===\nAs with many vernacular regions, North Florida does not have any officially designated boundaries or status, and is defined differently in different sources. A 2007 study of Florida's regions by geographers Ary Lamme and Raymond K. Oldakowski found that Floridians surveyed identified \"North Florida\" as comprising the northernmost areas of the state, including both the peninsula and the [[Florida Panhandle]]. Additionally, two localized \"directional\" regions had emerged: [[North East Florida]], also known as the \"First Coast\", representing the area around [[Jacksonville]] on the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]] coast, and [[North Central Florida]], comprising the central area.<ref name=Lamme329>Lamme & Oldakowsi, p. 329.</ref> North Florida is one of Florida's three most common directional regions, along with [[Central Florida]] and [[South Florida]].<ref name=Lamme335>Lamme & Oldakowski, p. 335.</ref> The region includes smaller vernacular regions, particularly along the coast, including the [[Emerald Coast]] and the [[Big Bend (Florida)|Big Bend]] on the [[Gulf Coast]] and the [[First Coast]] and [[Halifax area]] on the [[Atlantic Ocean|Atlantic]].<ref name=Lamme329/> Lamme and Oldakowski note that the directional region is more commonly used in the interior areas than on the coast.<ref name=\"Lamme335\"/>\n\nEnterprise Florida, the state's [[economic development agency]], divides the state into three economic regions, used within the agency and other state and outside entities, including the [[Florida Department of Transportation]]. They identify three regions within the area identified as \"North Florida\" by Enterprise Florida: Northeast Florida, North Central Florida, and Northwest Florida (representing most of the Panhandle).<ref>\"Charting the Course\", p. 2\u20133.</ref>\n\n===Regions===\nThe following regions are entirely or partly within Northern Florida:\n{{Columns-start|num=3}}\n'''Directional regions:'''\n*[[Northeast Florida]]\n*[[North Central Florida]]\n*[[Northwest Florida]]\n\n{{Column}}\n'''Metropolitan areas:'''\n*[[Jacksonville, FL MSA|Jacksonville]]\n*[[Pensacola-Ferry Pass-Brent, FL MSA|Pensacola]]\n*[[Tallahassee, FL MSA|Tallahassee]]\n*[[Ocala, FL MSA|Ocala]]\n*[[Gainesville, FL MSA|Gainesville]]\n*[[Crestview-Fort Walton Beach-Destin, FL MSA|Fort Walton Beach]]\n*[[Panama City-Lynn Haven-Panama City Beach, FL MSA|Panama City]]\n*[[Palm Coast, FL MSA|Palm Coast]]\n\n{{Column}}\n'''Vernacular regions:'''\n*[[Big Bend (Florida)|Big Bend]]\n*[[Emerald Coast]]\n*[[First Coast]]\n*[[Florida Panhandle]]\n*[[Forgotten Coast]]\n*[[Halifax area]]\n*[[Nature Coast]]\n{{Columns-end}}\n\n===Cityscapes===\n{{wide image|TallahasseeCityscape.png|1000px|align-cap=center|[[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]], the capital of the [[State of Florida]].}}\n{{wide image|Jaxnorthbankskyline.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|[[Jacksonville]], the most populous city proper in the [[Southeastern United States|Southeast]], and twelfth most populous in the United States.}}\n{{wide image|St. Augustine Florida Panoramic View.jpg|1000px|align-cap=center|[[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]], the oldest continuously occupied European-established settlement and port in the continental United States.}}\n\n===Climate===\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n| colspan=\"13\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:120%;background:#E8EAFA;\"|Average High and Low temperatures for various North Florida Cities\n|- style=\"background:#e5afaa; color:#000\"\n| '''City'''\n| '''Jan'''\n| '''Feb'''\n| '''Mar'''\n| '''Apr'''\n| '''May'''\n| '''Jun'''\n| '''Jul'''\n| '''Aug'''\n| '''Sep'''\n| '''Oct'''\n| '''Nov'''\n| '''Dec'''\n|- style=\"background:#f8f3ca; color:#000\"\n|[[Jacksonville, Florida|Jacksonville]]<ref name=\"jaxweather\">{{cite web|url = http://www.nws.noaa.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=jax |title = NowData \u2013 NOAA Online Weather Data |publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate =August 1, 2013}}</ref>\n| 65/42\n| 68/45\n| 74/50\n| 79/55\n| 86/63\n| 90/70\n| 92/73\n| 91/73\n| 87/69\n| 80/61\n| 74/51\n| 67/44\n|- style=\"background:#c5dfe1; color:#000\"\n| [[Pensacola, Florida|Pensacola]]<ref name=\"pnsweather\">{{cite web|url = http://www.nws.noaa.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=pns |title = NowData \u2013 NOAA Online Weather Data |publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate =August 1, 2013}}</ref>\n| 61/43\n| 64/46\n| 70/51\n| 76/58\n| 84/66\n| 89/72\n| 90/74\n| 90/74\n| 87/70\n| 80/60\n| 70/50\n| 63/45\n|- style=\"background:#f8f3ca; color:#000\"\n| [[Tallahassee, Florida|Tallahassee]]<ref name=\"tlhweather\">{{cite web|url = http://www.nws.noaa.gov/climate/xmacis.php?wfo=tae |title = NowData&nbsp;\u2014 NOAA Online Weather Data |publisher = [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] |accessdate =August 1, 2013}}</ref>\n| 64/39\n| 68/42\n| 74/47\n| 80/52\n| 87/62\n| 91/70\n| 92/72\n| 92/72\n| 89/68\n| 82/57\n| 73/48\n| 66/41\n|}</center>\n\n==Demographics==\n[[Jacksonville metropolitan area|Jacksonville]] is the largest [[metropolitan area]] in North Florida. Its cities include [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]], [[Orange Park, Florida|Orange Park]], and [[Fernandina Beach]], this area is sometimes referred to as the [[First Coast]]. Other metropolitan areas include [[Pensacola-Ferry Pass-Brent, FL MSA|Pensacola-Ferry Pass-Brent]], [[Tallahassee, FL MSA|Tallahassee]], [[Ocala, FL MSA|Ocala]], [[Gainesville, FL MSA|Gainesville]], [[Crestview-Fort Walton Beach-Destin, FL MSA|Crestview-Fort Walton Beach-Destin]], [[Panama City-Lynn Haven-Panama City Beach, FL MSA|Panama City-Lynn Haven]], and [[Palm Coast, FL MSA|Palm Coast]]. Important cities considered micropolitan areas include [[Lake City, Florida|Lake City]] and [[Palatka, Florida|Palatka]].\n\n===Largest cities by population===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! City\n! 2010 population<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bebr.ufl.edu/population/population-data/florida-population-census-summary-2010 |title=Florida Population: Census Summary 2010 |year=2011 |author=Bureau of Economic and Business Research |publisher=University of Florida }}</ref>\n! 2000 population\n! County\n|-\n| Jacksonville\n| 821,784\n| 735,617\n| Duval\n|-\n| Tallahassee\n| 181,376\n| 150,624\n| Leon\n|-\n| Gainesville\n| 124,354\n| 95,447\n| Alachua\n|-\n| Palm Coast\n| 75,180\n| 32,732\n| Flagler\n|-\n| Ocala\n| 56,315\n| 45,943\n| Marion\n|-\n| Pensacola\n| 51,923\n| 56,255\n| Escambia\n|}\n\n==Culture==\n\n[[File:Apalachicola HD Gibson Inn01.jpg|thumb|Historic Gibson Inn, Apalachicola, Florida, built in 1907.]]\nLamme and Oldakowski's survey identifies several demographic, political, and cultural elements that characterize North Florida and distinguish it from other areas of the state. North Floridians considered their area to be part of the [[Southern United States|South]] and \"[[Dixie]]\"; while Floridians from all parts of the state considered their area to be part of the South, people in more southern areas typically did not identify with Dixie. Additionally, residents of some parts of North Florida considered their area to be in the [[Bible Belt]], while residents of other parts of the state did not.<ref name=Lamme329/> A popular expression of people in this region of the state goes \"In Florida, the farther north you go, the farther south you are.\"\n\nPolitically, in contrast to Central Florida, where a majority considered their part of the state moderate, and South Florida, which was more liberal, residents of North Florida overwhelmingly (76%) considered their part of the state conservative; 16% considered it moderate and 8% considered it liberal.<ref name=Lamme336>Lamme & Oldakowsi, p. 336.</ref> Lamme and Oldakowski's findings track with Barney Warf and Cynthia Waddell's studies of Florida's political geography during the [[2000 United States presidential election|2000 Presidential election]].<ref name=Lamme336/><ref>Warf & Waddell, pp. 88.</ref>\n[[File:Ray Charles Childhood Home historical marker, Greenville.JPG|thumb|Located in North Florida is Ray Charles, American singer-songwriter, musician, and composer's childhood home, Greenville, Madison County, Florida.]]\nLamme and Oldakowski's survey also found some cultural indicators that characterize North Florida. In general, North Florida was similar to Central Florida and differed from South Florida in these measures. In North and Central Florida, [[American cuisine]] was the most popular food, in contrast to South Florida, where ethnic foods were equally popular.<ref name=Lamme337>Lamme & Oldakowsi, p. 337.</ref> Additionally, while there was little geographical variation for most styles of music, there was regional variation for both [[country music|country]] and [[Latin music (genre)|Latin]] music. Country was popular in North and Central Florida, and less so in South Florida, while Latin was less popular in North and Central Florida, and more so in South Florida.<ref name=Lamme337/>\n\n==Economy==\n[[File:LaurastBOAT.jpg|thumb|upright|right|[[Bank of America Tower (Jacksonville)|Bank of America Tower]] located on [[Laura Street]], in Jacksonville's financial district]]\n[[File:Old Slave Market, Saint Augustine, Florida.jpg|thumb|Old Slave Market, Saint Augustine, Florida]]\nLamme and Oldakowski noted that North Florida's economy was much more diversified than Central and South Florida, where tourism was by far the most significant industry. While tourism was a significant factor in North Florida's economy, particularly in the Emerald Coast and Daytona areas, other important industries included agriculture in rural areas, education in Tallahassee and Gainesville, and military and finance in Jacksonville.<ref>Lamme & Oldakowsi, pp. 336\u2013337.</ref>\n\nMajor military bases in the region include the [[Pensacola Naval Air Station]], [[Jacksonville Naval Air Station]], [[Camp Blanding]], [[Naval Station Mayport]], [[Corry Station Naval Technical Training Center]], [[Naval Support Activity Panama City]], [[Blount Island Command]], [[Eglin Air Force Base]] and [[Hurlburt Field]].\n\nMajor attractions include the [[Big Kahuna's]], [[Marineland of Florida]], [[Florida State Capitol]], [[World Golf Village]], [[Historic Pensacola Village]], and historic sites in [[St. Augustine, Florida|St. Augustine]]. North Florida also has a wide variety of natural attractions including the [[Ravine Gardens State Park]], [[Big Lagoon State Park]], [[Ocala National Forest]], [[Osceola National Forest]], and [[Timucuan Ecological and Historic Preserve]]. North Florida also has three major [[zoos]], the [[Jacksonville Zoo and Gardens]], [[St. Augustine Alligator Farm Zoological Park]] and [[Gulf Breeze Zoo]].\n[[File:Lynyrd Skynyrd band (1973).jpg|thumb|North Florida was the birthplace of the Southern Rock band Lynyrd Skynyard. Inducted into the [[Rock and Roll Hall of Fame]] on March 13, 2006, the band's lead singer, Ronnie Van Zant was born & raised in Jacksonville, Florida. ]]\nMajor malls and shopping districts include [[The Avenues (shopping mall)|The Avenues]], [[Butler Plaza]], [[Five Points (Jacksonville)|Five Points]], [[Gateway Town Center]], [[Governor's Square]], [[Jacksonville Landing]], [[The Oaks Mall]], [[Orange Park Mall]], [[Paddock Mall]], [[Pier Park (Florida)|Pier Park]], [[Regency Square Mall (Jacksonville)|Regency Square]], [[River City Marketplace]], [[St. Johns Town Center]] and [[University Town Plaza]].\n\n===Major business districts===\nThe following are major central business districts:\n*[[Downtown Jacksonville]]\n*[[Downtown Pensacola]]\n*[[File:Lois Duncan Steinmetz gazing at the Suwannee River (8670981193).jpg|thumb|The Suwannee River, is a blackwater [[river]] that runs through North [[Florida]] and is about 246 miles (396 km) long. The Suwannee River is the site of the prehistoric [[Gulf Trough|Suwanee Straits]] which separated peninsular Florida from the panhandle. ]][[Tallahassee|Downtown Tallahassee]]\n\n=== Notable companies ===\n{{See also|Category:Companies based in North Florida}}\n[[File:View of visitors on tour inside cave at the Florida Caverns State Park- Marianna, Florida (3247325003).jpg|thumb|In North Florida is Florida Caverns State Park, Marianna, Florida.]]\nThousands of companies are headquartered in North Florida. Among those, the following 4 are in the [[Fortune 1000]]:\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[CSX Corporation]]\n* [[Fidelity National Financial]]\n* [[FIS (company)|FIS]]\n* [[Landstar System]]\n}}\n\nAdditional notable companies headquartered (or with a significant presence) in North Florida include (some defunct or subsumed):\n{{Columns-list|\n* [[AirScan]]\n* [[All Pro Sound]]\n* [[Ameris Bancorp]]\n* [[Acosta Sales & Marketing]]\n* [[Atlantic.net]]\n* [[Bear Archery]]\n* [[Black Knight (company)|Black Knight]]\n* [[Bloch Publishing Company]]\n* [[Caribiana Sea Skiffs]]\n* [[Crowley Maritime]]\n* [[Elkins Constructors]]\n* [[EnCor Biotechnology]]\n* [[Fanatics (sports retailer)|Fanatics]]\n* [[Firehouse Subs]]\n* [[FRP Holdings]]\n* [[Blue Cross Blue Shield Association|Florida Blue]]\n* [[Florida East Coast Railway]]\n* [[Gate Petroleum]]\n* [[Gulf Power Company]]\n* [[The Haskell Company|Haskell Company]]\n* [[Huckins Yacht Corporation]]\n* [[KBJ Architects]]\n* [[Larry's Giant Subs]]\n* [[M. D. Moody & Sons, Inc.|M. D. Moody & Sons]]\n* [[Mac Papers]]\n* [[MedMal Direct Insurance Company]]\n* [[MOBRO Marine, Inc.|MOBRO Marine]]\n* [[Patriot Transportation]]\n* [[PGA Tour]]\n* [[Rayonier]]\n* [[Rayonier Advanced Materials]]\n* [[Regency Centers Corporation|Regency Centers]]\n* [[Reynolds, Smith & Hills]]\n* [[Ring Power]]\n* [[Safariland]]\n* [[St. Joe Company]]\n* [[St. Vincent's HealthCare]]\n* [[Sally Corporation]]\n* [[Seward Trunk Co.]]\n* [[Southeastern Grocers]]\n* [[Stein Mart]]\n* [[Stellar Group (construction company)|Stellar Group]]\n* [[Swisher International Group]]\n* [[Trailer Bridge]]\n* [[Trendy Entertainment]]\n* [[US Assure]]\n* [[VyStar Credit Union]]\n* [[Web.com]]\n}}\n\n==Parks and other protected areas==\n===National Monuments and other federally protected areas===\n{{Main|List of National Monuments of the United States|List of U.S. National Forests}}\nAreas under federal protection include [[Castillo de San Marcos National Monument]], [[Fort Matanzas National Monument]], [[Fort Caroline National Memorial]], [[Gulf Islands National Seashore]], and [[Timucuan Ecological and Historic Preserve]]. [[United States National Forest|National forests]] occupy large sections of North Florida, including the [[Apalachicola National Forest]], [[Choctawhatchee National Forest]], [[Ocala National Forest]], and [[Osceola National Forest]].\n\n===Other parks and protected areas===\n{{Expand list|date=August 2008}}\n{{Columns-start|num=3}}\n*[[Waccasassa Bay Preserve State 