-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133868|desc= Milestone opposite junction with Towngate at NGR SE 157 232, Brighouse|access-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133850|desc= Civic Hall, Brighouse|access-date= 8 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1183673|desc= Barclays Bank, Brighouse|access-date= 6 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133837|desc= Boundary stone, 130 metres west of Rawson's Arms at NGR SE 115223, Brighouse|access-date= 6 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133851|desc= Park Methodist Church and attached Sunday School, Brighouse|access-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133856|desc= Town Hall, Brighouse|access-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1134345|desc= Calder and Hebble Navigation Kirklees Cut Brearley Bridge, Brighouse|access-date= 7 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133855|desc= National Westminster Bank, Brighouse|access-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1183964|desc= Bethel Methodist Church with integral Sunday School, Brighouse|access-date= 6 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1419209|desc= Reconstructed Roman Watchtower, Brighouse|access-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{NHLE |num= 1133839|desc= War Memorial in Rydings Park, Brighouse|access-date= 9 April 2020|mode=cs2|fewer-links=yes}}\n*{{Citation | author = Historic England | title = Listed Buildings | url = http://www.historicengland.org.uk/listing/what-is-designation/listed-buildings/ |accessdate= 6 April 2020}}\n*{{Citation | last =Harman| first =Ruth| authorlink = | last2 = Pevsner | first2 = Nikolaus | author2-link = Nikolaus Pevsner | series= The Buildings of England| title =Yorkshire West Riding: Sheffield and the South |edition= | publisher =[[Yale University Press]] | year =2017 | location =New Haven and London | isbn =978-0-300-22468-9}}\n{{Refend}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Brighouse)}}\n[[Category:Lists of listed buildings in West Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "[[Brighouse]] is a town and an unparished area in the [[metropolitan borough]] of [[Calderdale]], [[West Yorkshire]], England.   It contains 71 [[Listed building#England and Wales|listed buildings]] that are recorded in the [[National Heritage List for England]].  Of these, two are listed at Grade&nbsp;I, the highest of the three grades, six are at Grade&nbsp;II*, the middle grade, and the others are at Grade&nbsp;II, the lowest grade.  This list contains the listed buildings in Brighouse Ward which, in addition to the town of Brighouse, contains the village of [[Clifton, West Yorkshire|Clifton]] and the surrounding countryside, in particular to the west and the southeast of the town along the valley of the [[River Calder, West Yorkshire|River Calder]].  Historically, one of the most important buildings in the area was [[Kirklees Priory]], which has been demolished, but listed buildings associated with it remain, in particular farm buildings in Home Farm and a [[gatehouse]].  In addition to the River Calder, the [[Calder and Hebble Navigation]] runs through the area, and listed buildings associated with the two waterways include bridges, [[lock (water navigation)|locks]], lock keepers' houses, a warehouse, and a milestone.  The other listed buildings include houses and associated structures, cottages, farmhouses and farm buildings, shops and offices, churches and chapels, two graves, a [[sundial]], a former mill, a former school, civic buildings, banks, a railway bridge, road milestones, a boundary stone, a [[folly]], and a war memorial.\n__NOTOC__\n==Key==\n{{GeoGroupTemplate}}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Grade\n! Criteria{{sfn|Historic England|ps=none}}\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade I colour}}|I\n| Buildings of exceptional interest, sometimes considered to be internationally important\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|II*\n| Particularly important buildings of more than special interest\n|-\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|II\n| Buildings of national importance and special interest\n|}\n\n==Buildings==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"width:100%; border:0; text-align:left; line-height:150%;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:150px\" |Name and location\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:100px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Photograph\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:120px\" |Date\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:650px\" class=\"unsortable\"|Notes\n! scope=\"col\"  style=\"width:50px\" |Grade\n|-\n|The Nuns Grave<br/><small>{{coord|53.69520|-1.73591|type:landmark|name=Double-aisled barn, Home Farm}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1300|Medieval}}\n|Two table tombs, one a [[England in the Middle Ages|medieval]] slab with an engraved [[crucifix]], the other an inscribed slab from the 18th century.  They are surrounded by octagonal tapered stone columns with pointed caps and the remains of iron railings.{{sfnp|Historic England|1133847|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|1 and 3 Upper Green Lane<br/><small>{{coord|53.71511|-1.79680|type:landmark|name=1 and 3 Upper Green Lane}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1400|Late Medieval}}\n|Formerly Netherhouse, the house has a [[timber framed]] core, and it was later encased in stone.  The house has a stone slate roof, two storeys and three [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  In the middle bay is a 16-light [[mullion]]ed and [[transom (architecture)|transomed]] window and a four-light fire window, and the other windows have altered glazing.  Above the ground floor windows are [[slate]] [[hood mould]]s, and under the [[eaves]] is a [[string course]] of diagonally-set slates.  Inside there is exposed timber framing.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|pp=148\u2013149|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1314090|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Double-aisled barn,<br/>Home Farm<br/><small>{{coord|53.69541|-1.73743|type:landmark|name=Double-aisled barn, Home Farm}}</small>\n|[[File:Stable block and ancient barn, Kirklees Home Farm, Clifton - geograph.org.uk - 177764.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1450|15th century}}\n|The barn is double-[[aisle]]d with a [[timber framed]] core, external walls in stone and a stone slate roof.  There are six [[bay (architecture)|bays]] with cross-wings added in about 1620.  It has a later [[gable]]d porch, a square-headed entry, and a gabled wing, originally a [[dovecote]].  Added to the east is a stable block with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], a [[coping (architecture)|coped]] gable and kneelers.  There are two storeys and a loft, with stabling in the ground floor, a hay loft above, and living accommodation over that.  It contains [[mullion]]ed windows with [[hood mould]]s, a doorway with composite [[jamb]]s and a [[Tudor arch]]ed [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]] with [[spandrel]]s, and a pitching hole.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=372|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1133848|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade I colour}}|{{sort|a|I}}\n|-\n|L-shaped aisled barn,<br/>Home Farm<br/><small>{{coord|53.69592|-1.73727|type:landmark|name=L-shaped aisled barn, Home Farm}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1525|Early 16th century}}\n|The [[timber framed]] barn was encased in stone in the 17th century, and it has a stone slate [[hipped roof]].  There are two ranges, the main range with 5\u00bd&nbsp;[[bay (architecture)|bays]], and a cross-wing of two bays with an [[aisle]].{{sfnp|Historic England|1133808|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Kirklees Priory Gatehouse<br/><small>{{coord|53.69517|-1.73725|type:landmark|name=Kirklees Priory Gatehouse}}</small>\n|[[File:Kirklees Priory Gatehouse, Clifton - geograph.org.uk - 177762.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1525|Early 16th century}}\n|The [[gatehouse]] was extended in the late 16th or early 17th century.  The original part has a [[timber framed]] core, its lower storey has been encased in stone, the extension is in stone, and the roof is in stone slate with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and kneelers.  There are two storeys and an attic.  The upper storey of west gable end is timber-framed and contains a four-light [[oriel window]], a decorated tie-beam and a [[finial]].  There is a doorway in the ground floor, and another doorway in the north front approached by steps.  A [[string course]] goes round the building, and the windows are [[mullion]]ed, some with [[hood mould]]s.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=372|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1314039|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Orchard walls, [[Kirklees Priory]]<br/><small>{{coord|53.69484|-1.73647|type:landmark|name=Orchard walls, Kirklees Priory}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1525|Early 16th century}}\n|The [[dry stone]] walls enclose the former orchard of the priory.  They are surmounted by a triangular [[Gothic architecture|Gothic]] ridge [[molding (architecture)|moulded]] at the apex.  In the angles are [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], and in the west wall is a [[chamfer]]ed gateway with composite [[jamb]]s.{{sfnp|Historic England|1300282|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Black Horse Hotel<br/><small>{{coord|53.69970|-1.75368|type:landmark|name=Black Horse Hotel}}</small>\n|[[File:Black Horse, Clifton, Brighouse (8074778663).jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1550|Mid 16th century}}\n|Three cottages combined to form a public house.  There is evidence of [[timber framing]] at the rear, and the building was rebuilt in the 18th century.  It is in stone with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], and a stone slate roof with a [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]] on the right.  There are two storeys and at the rear is a single-storey [[aisle]].  The windows are [[mullion]]ed, two doorways have tie-stone [[jamb]]s, and the other has [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] jambs.{{sfnp|Historic England|1133826|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|[[Kirklees Hall]] and stables<br/><small>{{coord|53.69632|-1.74354|type:landmark|name=Kirklees Hall}}</small>\n|\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1550|Mid 16th century}}\n|A [[English country house|country house]] that has been altered and extended, including in about 1770 by [[John Carr (architect)|John Carr]], it has later been converted into apartments.  It is in stone, and has a [[hip roof|hipped]] [[slate]] roof.  The north front has an E-shaped plan, with a central porch and projecting wings, and it contains [[sash window]]s.  Behind it are two wings, the southeast wing with three storeys and a staircase tower with a small octagonal spire.  To the west is a ten-[[bay (architecture)|bay]] service wing forming the north side of a courtyard that has a single-storey range on the west.  On the south side is a stable range with [[mullion]]ed windows, a [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]] with [[finial]]s, and a [[cupola]].{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|pp=372\u2013373|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1184034|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade I colour}}|{{sort|a|I}}\n|-\n|Sundial, Kirklees Park<br/><small>{{coord|53.69460|-1.73542|type:landmark|name=Sundial, Kirklees Park}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1617\n|The [[sundial]] was set on a new [[plinth]] in 1991, and moved to its present site in 1989.  It consists of a square stone slab with a bronze [[gnomon]] and an inscribed dial including a coat of arms.  It stands on a square plinth that has a [[chamfer]]ed base and cap, on an octagonal step, and it also carries inscriptions.{{sfnp|Historic England|1133846|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Barn northeast of 23&nbsp;Towngate<br/><small>{{coord|53.70435|-1.76204|type:landmark|name=Barn northeast of 23 Towngate}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1625|Early 17th century}}\n|The barn is in stone and has a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and kneelers.  There are five [[bay (architecture)|bays]] and an [[aisle]] on the west.  In the east front is an elliptical-arched doorway with [[monolithic architecture|monolithic]] [[jamb]]s, inserted windows, a lean-to and rectangular vents.  The west front has similar doorways and windows.{{sfnp|Historic England|1184373|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Single-aisled cow house,<br/>Home Farm<br/><small>{{coord|53.69561|-1.73703|type:landmark|name=Single-aisled cow house, Home Farm}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1625|Early 17th century}}\n|Originally [[timber framed]], the cow house has been enclosed in stone, and has a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and kneelers.  There are two [[bay (architecture)|bays]] and a single [[aisle]].  In the gable end are three doorways; the doorway to the aisle has a [[four-centred arch]]ed head and [[spandrel]]s, the others have depressed arches, and all have [[molding (architecture)|moulded]] [[jamb]]s.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=372|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1133805|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Two-cell house, Home Farm<br/><small>{{coord|53.69601|-1.73748|type:landmark|name=Two-cell house, Home Farm}}</small>\n|[[File:Former slaughter house, Kirklees Home Farm, Clifton - geograph.org.uk - 178225.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1625|Early 17th century}}\n|The building is in stone with a [[string course]], and a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and kneelers.  There are two storeys and two [[bay (architecture)|bays]].  The windows are double [[chamfer]]ed and [[mullion]]ed, and in the north gable end is a doorway with composite [[jamb]]s and a [[Tudor arch]]ed [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]].{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=372|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1314059|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Highley Hall and Barn<br/><small>{{coord|53.70315|-1.75975|type:landmark|name=Highley Hall}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1632\n|The house and barn are in stone with stone slate roofs.  The house has two storeys and an attic, a symmetrical front of three [[bay (architecture)|bays]], and a [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]] with kneelers and lantern [[finial]]s.  The outer bays contains gabled porches with coping, kneelers and lantern finials, and they contain doorways with [[Tudor arch]]ed [[lintel (architecture)|lintels]] and [[spandrel]]s.  The windows are [[mullion]]ed with a continuous [[hood mould]] over the porches and ground floor windows, and in the left return is a twelve-light mullioned and [[transom (architecture)|transomed]] window.  The barn has a segmental-arched cart entry with composite [[jamb]]s on the left, and there is a half-[[aisle]] with Tudor arched doorways.{{sfnp|Historic England|1314067|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II* colour}}|{{sort|b|II*}}\n|-\n|Cross Platts Farmhouse<br/><small>{{coord|53.70954|-1.81600|type:landmark|name=Cross Platts Farmhouse}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1635|Early to mid 17th century}}\n|The house is in [[stucco|rendered]] stone and has a stone slate roof.  There are two storeys, and it consists of a two-[[bay (architecture)|bay]] hall range with a [[gable]]d projecting cross-wing on the left.  The arched doorway has [[chamfer]]ed composite [[jamb]]s and [[spandrel]]s, most of the windows have double chamfered [[mullion]]s, and some have [[hood mould]]s.{{sfnp|Historic England|1183806|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Slead Hall<br/><small>{{coord|53.71128|-1.79374|type:landmark|name=Slead Hall}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|1636\n|The oldest part is the hall and a cross-wing, with additional wings added in 1718.  The house is in stone with a [[parapet]], an irregular plan, and a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s and lantern [[finial]]s.  The south front has a hall range of two [[bay (architecture)|bays]], the original gabled cross-wing on the right, and the later gabled wings on the left.  The windows vary; some are [[mullion]]ed and [[transom (architecture)|transomed]], and others are [[sash window|sashes]].  The entrance is through a [[portico]] added in the 1880s, which has open [[arcade (architecture)|arcades]] with square columns and finials.  The doorway has [[molding (architecture)|moulded]] composite [[jamb]]s and an arched [[lintel (architecture)|lintel]] with sunken [[spandrel]]s.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=148|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1314034|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Four-bay barn, Home Farm<br/><small>{{coord|53.69561|-1.73791|type:landmark|name=Four-bay barn, Home Farm}}</small>\n|{{centre|\u2014}}\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1675|Late 17th century}}\n|The barn, probably originally [[timber framed]] and later encased in stone.  It has four [[bay (architecture)|bays]], a central threshing door, and two floors at the south end.{{sfnp|Harman|Pevsner|2017|p=372|ps=none}}{{sfnp|Historic England|1314058|ps=none}}\n|align=\"center\" {{Grade II colour}}|{{sort|c|II}}\n|-\n|Malthouse, Home Farm<br/><small>{{coord|53.69640|-1.73905|type:landmark|name=Malthouse, Home Farm}}</small>\n|[[File:Malthouse, Kirklees Home Farm, Clifton - geograph.org.uk - 177720.jpg|100px|centre]]\n|align=\"center\"|{{sort|1675|Late 17th century}}\n|The [[malthouse]] is in stone on a [[plinth]], with [[quoin (architecture)|quoins]], [[string course]]s, and a stone slate roof with [[coping (architecture)|coped]] [[gable]]s, kneelers, and bases for [[finial]]s.  There are three storeys an